    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Japan's Political System Freezes Out Reformers; In Russia, Same Old</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eugene Salorio letter on July 7 article questions international money police defense of sacrifices forced on older generation of Russian workers during ostensible transition to free market economy</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Russia's ostensible transition to a free market economy leads it to stop paying salaries and pensions and to destroy its social safety net (Op-Ed, July 7).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Russia's ostensible transition to a free market economy leads it to stop paying salaries and pensions and to destroy its social safety net (Op-Ed, July 7).</p>
        <p>The international money police argue that the eventual benefits of this shift to nomenklatura capitalism (based on who has grabbed ownership of former state assets) justify what amounts to the sacrifice of the older generation of less endowed Russian workers.</p>
        <p>Perhaps the international money police should reflect on the parallels to apologists for the Soviets, who justified the forced industrialization of the 1930's and the sacrifice of that generation for another supposed glorious future.  EUGENE SALORIO  Storrs, Conn., July 8, 1998</p>
      </block>
